<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-673-793  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 673 793.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 10 1990 v7 n49 p164(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft invests in Natural Language database tools.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fisher, Susan E.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Investment activities)Natural Language Inc. (Securities).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Topic:     Software PublishersTrendsRelational Data BasesQuery LanguagesBusiness Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Susan E. FisherandM;Microsoft Corp. has increased its interest in a small software company whoseflagship product allows users to query relational databases in plain English.andM;The Redmond, Wash., company announced last week that it invested anadditional $1 million in Natural Language Inc. (NLI), giving it more than a10 percent share of the private Berkeley, Calif., company.andM;Microsoft and NLI officials said the two companies will work together toinvestigate ways to integrate natural language technology in Microsoftproducts.andM;Tania Amochaev, NLI president and CEO, said, &quot;Accessing computers in Englishwill really be the way to open them to greater numbers of users.&quot;andM;Microsoft has been an investor in the 6-year-old company since June 1987.andP;  Atthat time, the companies signed an agreement granting Microsoft rights tointegrate NLI technology with Microsoft products, which the company has yetto do.andM;Backed by $12.2 million of equity financing, NLI sells its database tools asa companion to major relational database-management systems (DBMSs).andP;  NaturalLanguage software runs on Unix computers.andM;More than 100 Fortune 1000 customers have purchased the Natural Languagesoftware, priced between $10,000 and $93,000.andM;Darryl Rubin, vice president of application strategy at Microsoft, said thesoftware's memory requirement, about 4M bytes, makes incorporating it into aproduct in the near future impractical.andO;</TEXT></DOC>